'''''Koinonos''''' ({{lang-grc-gre|κοινωνός}}) is an [[Ancient Greek]] word, generally thought to mean [[Friendship|companion]]; however it has been used extensively in ancient writing with a wide variety of meanings. Its original form is κοινωνός and it was later translated to Koinonos. one can read it as "koy-no-nos". It can mean married partner, business partner, friend or companion in faith as well. It is generally used with reference to "sharing".<ref name="Schaberg2004">{{cite book|author=Jane Schaberg|title=The Resurrection of Mary Magdalene: Legends, Apocrypha, and the Christian Testament|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0Mq1ckqdORUC&pg=PA152|accessdate=15 November 2012|date=31 August 2004|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8264-1645-2|pages=152–}}</ref><ref name="KellerKeller2006">{{cite book|author1=Virginia Burrus, Catherine Keller|author2=Catherine Keller|title=Toward a Theology of Eros: Transfiguring Passion at the Limits of Discipline|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mHzT57pDVi0C&pg=PA240|accessdate=15 November 2012|date=15 November 2006|publisher=Fordham Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8232-2636-8|pages=240–}}</ref> It has been used in the [[Gospel of Philip]] to note the relationship between Jesus and [[Mary Magdalene]].<ref name="Schaberg2004"/>

