{{about|an emotion|the album|Oceanic Feeling (album)}} In a 1927 letter to Sigmund Freud, [[Romain Rolland]] coined the phrase "'''oceanic feeling'''" to refer to the sensation of being one with the universe.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |last=Roberts |first=Robert |editor=[[Edward N. Zalta|Zalta, Edward N.]] |title=Emotions in the Christian Tradition |url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/emotion-Christian-tradition/ |encyclopedia=[[Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]] |volume=Winter 2016 |date=18 November 2016}}</ref> According to Rolland, this feeling is the source of all the religious energy that permeates in various religious systems, and one may justifiably call oneself religious on the basis of this oceanic feeling alone, even if one renounces every belief and every illusion.<ref>The Ontology of Religiosity: The Oceanic Feeling and the Value of the Lived Experience</ref> Freud discusses the feeling in his ''[[The Future of an Illusion|Future of an Illusion]]'' (1927) and ''[[Civilization and Its Discontents]]'' (1929). There he deems it a fragmentary vestige of a kind of consciousness possessed by an infant who has not yet differentiated himself or herself from other people and things.<ref>Freud, Sigmund. ''[[Civilization and Its Discontents]]'', [http://www.stephenhicks.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/FreudS-CIVILIZATION-AND-ITS-DISCONTENTS-text-final.pdf pp. 11–13].</ref>
== History == On December 5, 1927, Rolland coined the phrase in a [[Romain Rolland#Correspondence with Freud|letter to Freud]]:
{{quote|''Mais j'aurais aimé à vous voir faire l'analyse du sentiment religieux spontané ou, plus exactement, de la ''sensation'' religieuse qui est...le fait simple et direct de ''la sensation de l'Eternel'' (qui peut très bien n'être pas éternel, mais simplement sans bornes perceptibles, et comme océanique).''<ref>{{cite book |first=Jeffrey Moussaieff |last=Masson |authorlink=Jeffrey Moussaieff Masson |title=The Oceanic Feeling. The Origins of Religious Sentiment in Ancient India |url=https://books.google.com/?id=swsrBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |date=6 December 2012 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/?id=vBRnmMts8e4C 1st ed.: 1980] |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=swsrBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA34&dq=%22Mais+j'aurais+aimé+à+vous+voir+faire+l'analyse%22%22de+la+sensation+de+l'Eternel+(qui+peut+très+bien+n'étre+pas+éternel,+mais+simplement+sans+bornes+perceptibles,+et+comme+océanique%22 34] |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |id={{ISBN|9-40098969-5}} |isbn=978-9-400-98969-6}}</ref>}}
In strict translation:
{{quote|But I would have liked to see you doing an analysis of ''spontaneous religious sentiment'' or, more exactly, of religious ''feeling'', which is...the simple and direct fact ''of the feeling of the ‘eternal’'' (which can very well not be eternal, but simply without perceptible limits, and like oceanic, as it were).<ref>{{cite book |first=William B. |last=Parsons |title=The Enigma of the Oceanic Feeling. Revisioning the Psychoanalytic Theory of Mysticism |url=https://books.google.com/?id=keNYGu3bjOUC&printsec=frontcover |date=17 June 1999 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=keNYGu3bjOUC&pg=PA36&dq=%22But+I+would+have+liked+to+see+you+doing+an+analysis+of%22%22the+feeling+of+the+‘eternal’+(which+can+very+well+not+be+eternal,+but+simply+without+perceptible+limits,+and+like+oceanic+as+it+were).%22 36] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |id={{ISBN|0-19535408-7}} |isbn=978-0-195-35408-9}}</ref>}}
Freud ends ''The Future of an Illusion'' with a discussion of the concept, and picks up the discussion at the beginning of ''Civilization and Its Discontents'', answering Rolland's request. There he credits the concept to an anonymous friend.
== Freud's explanation == Freud argues that the "oceanic feeling", if it exists, is the preserved "primitive ego-feeling" from infancy. The primitive ego-feeling precedes the creation of the ego and exists up until the mother ceases breastfeeding. Prior to this, the infant is regularly breastfed in response to its crying and has no concept that the breast does not belong to it. Therefore, the infant has no concept of a "self" or, rather, considers the breast to be part of itself. Freud argues that those experiencing an oceanic feeling as an adult are actually experiencing a preserved primitive ego-feeling. The ego, in contrast, comes into existence when the breast is taken away, and involves the infant's recognition that it is separate from the mother's breast, and therefore, that other people exist. Freud argues that it would not necessarily contradict psychoanalytical theory for this primary ego-feeling to coexist along with the ego in some people. The main argument for this is that psychoanalytical theory holds that all thoughts are preserved in a conservation of psychic energy. Therefore, the "oceanic feeling" described as a oneness with the world or a limitlessness is simply a description of the feeling the infant has before it learns there are other persons in the world.
== Neuroscientific explanation == {{Main article|Neuroscience of religion}}
"Neurotheology" is a [[neologism]] that describes the scientific study of the neural correlates of religious or spiritual beliefs and practices. Other researchers have rejected the term, preferring to use terms like "spiritual neuroscience" or "neuroscience of religion". Researchers in the field attempt to explain the neurological basis for religious experiences, such as:<ref>{{cite book |first=Robert A. |last=Burton |authorlink=Robert A. Burton |title=On Being Certain. Believing You Are Right Even When You're Not |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PsYEOdPj78gC&printsec=frontcover |chapter=Neurotheology |chapterurl=https://books.google.it/?id=PsYEOdPj78gC&pg=PT36&dq=neurotheology+%22oneness+with+the+universe%22%22awe,+joy+and+a+general+sense+of+harmony+and+deep+significance%22 |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]/[[St. Martin's Press]] |location=New York City |date=5 February 2008}} {{ISBN|1-42992611-2}}; {{ISBN|978-1-429-92611-9}} (Macmillan Publishers edition). {{ISBN|0-31235920-9}}; {{ISBN|978-0-312-35920-1}} (St. Martin's Press edition).</ref> the perception that [[time]], [[fear]] or [[self-awareness|self-consciousness]] have dissolved; [[supernatural|spiritual]] awe; [[Monism|oneness]] with the universe; ecstatic [[altered state of consciousness|trance]]; sudden [[Enlightenment (spiritual)|enlightenment]]; and [[altered states of consciousness]].
What [[Andrew B. Newberg]] and others "discovered is that intensely focused [[meditation|spiritual contemplation]] triggers an alteration in the activity of the brain that leads one to perceive transcendent religious experiences as solid, tangible reality. In other words, the sensation that [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] call ''oneness with the universe''."<ref>{{cite book |author=Newberg, Andrew B. |authorlink=Andrew B. Newberg |author2=D'Aquili, Eugene G. |author2link=Eugene G. d'Aquili |author3=Rause, Vince |title=Why God Won't Go Away. Brain Science and the Biology of Belief |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:www.andrewnewberg.com/books/why-god-wont-go-away-brain-science-the-biology-of-belief+%22discovered+was+that+intensely+focused+spiritual+contemplation+triggers+an+alteration+in+the+activity+of+the+brain+that+leads+one+to+perceive+transcendent+religious+experiences+as+solid,+tangible+reality.+In+other+words,+the+sensation+that+Buddhists+call%22%22oneness+with+the+universe%22 |publisher=[[Ballantine Books]] |location=New York City |year=2002 |isbn=0-345-44034-X}}</ref>
